{
  "enabled": true,
  "name": "1 · AM: Morning Routine",
  "version": "5.1.0",
  "description": "One-click morning: Asana sync → draft replies → task refresh + daily brief → calendar blocks.",
  "when": {
    "type": "userTriggered"
  },
  "then": {
    "type": "askAgent",
    "prompt": "Run Richard's morning routine. 4 steps (5 on Fridays), in order. Each step feeds the next.\\n\\nCONTEXT LOAD (do this once, before Step 1):\\nORDER MATTERS. Reference files first, action-critical last.\\n1. ~/shared/context/body/body.md\\n2. ~/shared/context/body/spine.md\\n3. ~/shared/context/active/org-chart.md\\n4. ~/.kiro/steering/richard-writing-style.md\\n5. ~/shared/context/active/current.md\\n6. ~/shared/context/body/memory.md\\n7. ~/shared/context/meetings/README.md (for meeting prep — series files loaded on demand per today's calendar)\\n8. ~/shared/context/body/amcc.md (LAST — freshest)\\n9. SLACK SCAN (invisible — not a numbered step for Richard):\\n   a. Load ~/shared/context/active/slack-channel-registry.json\\n   b. Load ~/shared/context/active/slack-scan-state.json\\n   c. Scan Tier 1 channels for messages since last morning routine timestamp using batch_get_conversation_history\\n   d. Scan Tier 2 channels only if their scan_interval_hours has elapsed\\n   e. Scan DM conversations with People Watch contacts (from channel registry → people_watch)\\n   f. Run Relevance Filter (see SLACK RELEVANCE FILTER below) on all retrieved messages\\n   g. If relevant signals found: produce ~/shared/context/intake/slack-digest-{YYYY-MM-DD-HHmm}.md\\n   h. Update ~/shared/context/active/slack-scan-state.json with new timestamps and tool invocation log\\n   i. On rate limit or API error: log to scan state errors array, continue with other data sources\\n   j. Cold start (no scan state file): scan only last 24 hours per channel\n   k. PROACTIVE SEARCH (runs after channel scans, same cycle):\n      - Load proactive_searches from channel registry\n      - Run priority 1 queries always, priority 2 if budget allows, priority 3 on morning routine only\n      - Each query: append 'after:{last_scan_date}' to scope results to new messages\n      - Dedup: skip results already captured by channel scans (same channel_id + ts)\n      - Apply same relevance filter to search results\n      - Include relevant signals in the Slack digest alongside channel signals\n      - Cap: max 10 queries, max 20 results per query, max 10 signals from search total\n   l. RSW-CHANNEL INTAKE SCANNING (runs during rsw-channel scan in step c above):\n      - When scanning rsw-channel (C0993SRL6FQ), check each message's author_id:\n        • If author_id == U040ECP305S (Richard) AND message text does NOT start with any system_message_markers from rsw_channel_behavior config in slack-channel-registry.json (\"Daily Brief —\", \"System Dashboard\", \"📋\", \"🖥️\", \"[DRAFT for\"): this is an intake message from Richard's phone.\n          → Create ~/shared/context/intake/rsw-intake-{YYYYMMDD-HHmm}.md with content: message text, any links, timestamp.\n          → If message matches action_patterns from rsw_channel_behavior (\"remind me to\", \"follow up with\", \"todo:\", \"TODO\", \"need to\", \"don't forget\"): add [ACTION-RW] tag to the intake file.\n          → If message has file attachments: download via download_file_content and include content in the intake file.\n          → Intake file format:\n            # rsw-channel Intake — {date} {time} PT\n            Source: rsw-channel mobile drop\n            [ACTION-RW] (if action pattern matched)\n            {message text}\n            ---\n            Captured: {ISO timestamp}\n            Route: hands.md (if action item detected) or gut.md (general intake)\n        • If author_id != U040ECP305S: skip (not Richard's message).\n        • If message text starts with any system_message_markers: skip (system-posted message).\n   m. CONVERSATION DATABASE WRITES (runs at end of Slack scan cycle):\n      After all messages have been retrieved and signals extracted, batch-write to DuckDB:\n      1. For ALL messages retrieved (not just relevant ones — the DB is the complete record):\n         INSERT OR REPLACE INTO slack_messages (ts, channel_id, channel_name, thread_ts, author_id, author_alias, author_name, text_preview, full_text, is_richard, is_thread_reply, reply_count, reaction_count, richard_reacted, relevance_score, signal_type)\n         VALUES (...)\n         - text_preview = first 200 characters of message text\n         - is_richard = TRUE when author_id = 'U040ECP305S'\n         - relevance_score and signal_type from the relevance filter (NULL for messages below threshold)\n      2. For threads with replies:\n         INSERT OR REPLACE INTO slack_threads (thread_ts, channel_id, channel_name, topic_summary, participant_aliases, message_count, decision_extracted, action_items, first_ts, last_ts)\n         - topic_summary: 1-2 sentence synthesis of thread topic\n         - participant_aliases: comma-separated list\n         - decision_extracted: extracted decision text if any, NULL otherwise\n         - action_items: extracted action items if any, NULL otherwise\n      3. For each unique author encountered:\n         INSERT OR REPLACE INTO slack_people (user_id, alias, display_name, first_interaction, last_interaction, total_messages, dm_messages, channel_messages, channels_shared, relationship_tier)\n         - On new author: set first_interaction = today, total_messages = count from this cycle\n         - On existing author: update last_interaction, increment message counts\n         - relationship_tier: sync from People Watch status (always_high, boosted, candidate, none)\n      4. Use batch operations — accumulate all rows during the scan, execute as a single DuckDB transaction via execute_query at the end. Target: <30 seconds added per cycle.\n      5. If DuckDB write fails: log error, continue. Existing organ routing is unaffected — DB writes are additive, not blocking.\\n\\n=== STEP 1: ASANA SYNC ===\\nProtocol: ~/shared/context/active/asana-sync-protocol.md\\nScan Auto-Comms → extract Asana IDs → update hands.md with new/changed Asana tasks → log to changelog.md.\\n\\n=== STEP 2: DRAFT UNREAD REPLIES ===\\n** SAFETY: NEVER call email_reply, email_send, or email_forward. Only email_draft with operation='create' or operation='update'. **\\n\\n** DRAFT DEDUP RULE (CRITICAL): Before creating a new draft, scan the Drafts folder for an existing draft matching the same subject line or recipient. If a match exists, use email_draft operation='update' with the existing draftId + draftChangeKey to overwrite the body with fresh context. Only use operation='create' if no matching draft exists. This prevents duplicate drafts from accumulating across morning routine runs. **\\n\\nScan unread folders → triage → draft or update replies in Richard's voice → present for confirmation → save approved as drafts.\\n\\n=== STEP 3: TASK REFRESH + DAILY BRIEF ===\\nLoad additional context:\\n1. ~/.kiro/steering/rw-trainer.md\\n2. ~/.kiro/steering/rw-task-prioritization.md\\n3. ~/shared/context/body/device.md\\n4. ~/shared/context/body/gut.md\\n5. ~/shared/context/active/rw-tracker.md\\n6. ~/shared/context/body/brain.md\\n7. ~/shared/context/body/eyes.md\\n8. ~/shared/context/body/hands.md (LAST)\\n\\nPHASE 1 — REFRESH TASKS:\\nUpdate hands.md with fresh task state from email/calendar/Asana/Slack signals. Add new tasks, mark completed ones, update context on existing tasks. hands.md is the single source of truth for all task tracking. No external task management tools.\\n\\n1. Scan email/calendar for new signals.\\n2. Check if any meetings/ series files need updating (new Hedy sessions or email threads since last sync). If yes, follow the Multi-Source Ingestion Protocol in ~/shared/context/meetings/README.md.\\n3. Add new tasks discovered from signals to the appropriate priority section in hands.md.\\n4. Mark completed tasks based on email/Asana/Slack confirmation.\\n5. Update context on existing tasks with fresh information from today's scan.\\n6. Update rw-tracker.md, hands.md, amcc.md.\\n\\nPHASE 2 — DAILY BRIEF:\\nCheck today's calendar. Check ~/shared/context/active/morning-routine-experiments.md for the current experiment (if any) and apply it to this brief.\\n\\nBuild brief with these sections (ORDER MATTERS — action-first, reflection last):\\n1. TRAINER CHECK-IN (honest assessment, Five Levels, patterns — the lead)\\n2. TODAY'S MEETINGS (chronological, prep notes)\\n3. CALENDAR BLOCKS (the 4 blocks with contents)\\n4. PENDING REPLIES\\n5. DUE THIS WEEK\\n6. HEADS UP\\n7. aMCC STATUS (streak, hard thing, resistance — near the bottom, reflective)\\n8. SYSTEM HEALTH (one line, omit if clean)\\n\\nTone: tight, scannable, trainer-direct.\\nSave to ~/shared/research/daily-brief-latest.md.\\nEmail to prichwil@amazon.com. Subject: Daily Brief — [today's date]. AUTO-SEND, no confirmation needed.\\n\\n** EMAIL TEMPLATE (MANDATORY — use this HTML structure for every brief email): **\\nDark navy card-based layout. Transparent background. Inline CSS. Table-based for Outlook.\\n\\nDESIGN SYSTEM:\\n- Max width: 700px centered\\n- Background: transparent (adapts to light/dark mode)\\n- Card background: #030a14 (very dark navy)\\n- Card border: 1px solid #0e1a2e, border-radius 12px\\n- Internal dividers: 1px solid #0e1a2e\\n- Font: system stack (-apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, 'Helvetica Neue', sans-serif)\\n- Section headers: 10px uppercase, letter-spacing 5px, color #4a5a78\\n- Primary text: font-weight 300-400, color #e8ecf2\\n- Secondary text: color #6a7a98\\n- Tertiary text: color #3a4a68 or #4a5a78\\n- Padding: 24px inside cards, 32px horizontal margins, 24px between cards\\n- No images. No external resources. Pure inline HTML+CSS.\\n\\nSECTION ORDER:\\n1. Header (DAILY BRIEF + day/date, centered, outside cards)\\n2. TRAINER CHECK-IN (card — use internal hairline dividers to separate main message / action / context tiers)\\n3. HEADS UP (card — each item separated by internal hairline dividers)\\n4. SLACK OVERNIGHT (card — ONLY if Slack digest was produced during context load. Omit entirely if no relevant Slack activity. Top 5 signals by relevance score, capped at 150 words. Each signal: one row with type icon + summary + source channel in secondary text. [ACTION-RW] items highlighted in amber #d4880f. Same card design as other sections.)\\n5. TODAY (card — merged Day at a Glance + Schedule + Focus Blocks into ONE unified card. Structure: (a) AM/PM color bars at top showing time allocation proportionally (Sweep=#4caf82, Meetings=#e8b84c, Core=#5b9bd5, Engine Room=#a0a0b8, Admin=#e88c5b, bars in 2px solid #1e3050 border with 6px radius, time labels below), then (b) a unified timeline below the bars where each row is a time slot. For MEETINGS: show time in uppercase letter-spaced #4a5a78 left column, meeting name + one-liner context in right column. For FOCUS BLOCKS: show time left column, block emoji + name + inline task list in right column (use secondary color #6a7a98 for task details). This eliminates three separate sections into one scannable card. Internal hairline dividers between rows.)\\n6. SPEC SHEET (card — label|value rows SpaceX-style, labels uppercase letter-spaced left, values right-aligned)\\n7. T-MINUS COUNTDOWN (card — large 56px font-weight-200 countdown number centered, subtitle with deadline + hard thing name)\\n8. aMCC STATUS (card — 3-column stat row: Streak/Stalled/Window with 36px thin-weight numbers, separated by 1px vertical borders)\\n9. Footer (BODY SYSTEM + date + experiment status, centered, outside cards)\\n\\nSPECIAL RULES:\\n- T-minus countdown dynamically calculates days until the next major deadline (from amcc.md hard thing or highest-priority due date)\\n- Day at a Glance bars are proportional to actual time — calculate width percentages from meeting/block durations\\n- Heads Up items are each on their own row with dividers (not a single paragraph)\\n- Trainer check-in uses 3 tiers of text weight: 18px #e8ecf2 (main), 15px #6a7a98 (action), 13px #3a4a68 (context), separated by hairline dividers\\n- Spec sheet values use color coding: red (#c0392b) for urgent, amber (#d4880f) for overdue, green (#4a9a6a) for ready\\n- SLACK OVERNIGHT: only appears when Slack digest exists. If signals contain [ACTION-RW] items, those were already added to hands.md in Phase 1. Section uses same card styling. Omit if zero signals.\\n\\nPHASE 3 — SLACK DAILY BRIEF POST:\\nAfter generating and sending the daily brief email, ALSO post a condensed version to rsw-channel.\\n\\n1. Compose a condensed Slack version of the daily brief (≤300 words, Slack mrkdwn format).\\n2. Post to rsw-channel (C0993SRL6FQ) via post_message.\\n3. After posting, mark rsw-channel as unread by calling batch_set_last_read with the channel ID C0993SRL6FQ and a timestamp ONE TICK before the posted message's ts. This ensures Richard sees the notification. This is the standard pattern for any rsw-channel post Richard should see.\\n4. Post a NEW message each morning — do NOT edit a previous day's brief. Slack edit history creates confusion.\\n5. If post_message fails: log the error to ~/shared/context/active/slack-scan-state.json → last_scan.errors array and continue the remaining routine steps. Do not retry or block.\\n\\nContent sources:\\n- hands.md → top 3 priorities, pending action count\\n- Calendar → today's meetings (chronological)\\n- amcc.md → streak count, days since last artifact\\n- slack-scan-state.json → hot_topics.active (trending topics with channel count)\\n\\nSLACK DAILY BRIEF FORMAT (use this template, Slack mrkdwn):\\n```\\n📋 *Daily Brief — {date}*\\n\\n*TOP 3*\\n1. {priority 1}\\n2. {priority 2}\\n3. {priority 3}\\n\\n*CALENDAR*\\n• {time} — {meeting 1}\\n• {time} — {meeting 2}\\n\\n*STATUS*\\n📊 Pending actions: {count} | 🔥 aMCC streak: Day {N} | 📦 Last artifact: {N} days ago\\n\\n*HOT*\\n• {hot topic 1} — {channels, signals}\\n• {hot topic 2}\\n```\\n\\nFOCUS UPDATE (after daily brief post):\\nPost a separate FOCUS UPDATE message to rsw-channel (C0993SRL6FQ) listing the top items that changed since last run.\\n1. Compare current hands.md state against the previous run: identify new tasks added, tasks completed, items escalated or re-prioritized.\\n2. Compose a focus update message (≤150 words, Slack mrkdwn format) using this template:\\n```\\n🔄 *Focus Update — {date}*\\n\\n*NEW*\\n• {new task or action item}\\n\\n*DONE*\\n• {completed item}\\n\\n*ESCALATED*\\n• {re-prioritized or escalated item}\\n```\\n3. Post to rsw-channel (C0993SRL6FQ) via post_message.\\n4. After posting, mark rsw-channel as unread by calling batch_set_last_read with C0993SRL6FQ and a timestamp ONE TICK before the posted message's ts.\\n5. If no task changes since last run, skip the focus update post.\\n6. If post_message fails: log error to slack-scan-state.json → last_scan.errors, continue.\\n\\nPHASE 4 — DASHBOARD UPDATE:\\nAfter the daily brief post, update the live dashboard message in rsw-channel (C0993SRL6FQ).\\n\\nENRICHMENT: PROACTIVE DRAFT SUGGESTIONS (runs after dashboard update):\\n1. Query slack_messages for unanswered messages directed at Richard:\\n   - author_id != 'U040ECP305S' (not Richard)\\n   - AND (full_text contains 'prichwil' OR channel_id is a DM with Richard)\\n   - AND richard_reacted = FALSE\\n   - AND no reply from Richard in the same thread\\n   - AND message is 24+ hours old\\n2. For each unanswered message:\\n   a. Load memory.md relationship graph tone notes for the sender\\n   b. Load ~/shared/portable-body/voice/richard-style-slack.md if it exists\\n   c. Load thread context from slack_threads\\n   d. Generate a draft response matching tone + register + thread context\\n3. Post draft to rsw-channel (C0993SRL6FQ): \"[DRAFT for @{person} in #{channel}]: {draft text}\"\\n4. Use create_draft when available for the target channel, fall back to rsw-channel post\\n5. After posting, mark rsw-channel as unread via batch_set_last_read (timestamp one tick before posted message ts)\\n6. SKIP messages where Richard reacted with ANY emoji — a reaction IS a response\\n\\n1. Read dashboard.message_ts from ~/shared/context/active/slack-scan-state.json — this is the message to edit.\\n2. Compose fresh dashboard content in Slack mrkdwn using the 6-section format below.\\n3. Edit the existing message using the Slack MCP (edit the message at message_ts in C0993SRL6FQ).\\n4. After editing, mark rsw-channel as unread by calling batch_set_last_read with C0993SRL6FQ and a timestamp ONE TICK before the dashboard message_ts. Richard sees the updated dashboard as a notification.\\n5. Update slack-scan-state.json → dashboard.last_updated with current timestamp.\\n6. If edit fails: log error to slack-scan-state.json → last_scan.errors, continue. Dashboard stays stale until next successful update.\\n\\nDashboard data sources:\\n- hands.md → top 3 priorities, pending action count\\n- Calendar → today's meeting count\\n- amcc.md → streak counter, hard thing status, days since last artifact\\n- eyes.md → one-line status per market (AU, MX, US, EU5, JP, CA)\\n- brain.md → Five Levels current position and gate status\\n- slack-scan-state.json → hot_topics.active (trending topics with channel count and key participants)\\n\\nDASHBOARD FORMAT (Slack mrkdwn, edit existing pinned message):\\n```\\n🖥️ *System Dashboard* — Updated {date} {time} PT\\n\\n━━━ *TODAY* ━━━\\n1. {priority 1}\\n2. {priority 2}\\n3. {priority 3}\\n📊 Pending: {count} | 📅 Meetings: {count}\\n\\n━━━ *STREAK* ━━━\\n🔥 aMCC: Day {N} | Hard thing: {description} | 📦 Last ship: {N}d ago\\n\\n━━━ *MARKETS* ━━━\\n🇦🇺 AU: {one-line status}\\n🇲🇽 MX: {one-line status}\\n🇺🇸 US: {one-line status}\\n🇪🇺 EU5: {one-line status}\\n🇯🇵 JP: {one-line status}\\n🇨🇦 CA: {one-line status}\\n\\n━━━ *HOT TOPICS* ━━━\\n• {topic} — {channels, participants}\\n\\n━━━ *WAITING ON RICHARD* ━━━\\n• {person}: {what} ({age})\\n\\n━━━ *FIVE LEVELS* ━━━\\n{current level positions and gate status}\\n```\\n\\n=== STEP 4: CALENDAR BLOCKS (AUTO-CREATE) ===\\nCreate 4 focus blocks in today's calendar gaps. No confirmation needed. Follow safety hooks.\\n\\n1. 🧹 SWEEP (20-30 min, morning gap)\\n   Low-friction: messages, confirmations, triage. Max 2 tasks per block.\\n2. 🎯 CORE (30-60 min, largest gap — PROTECT THIS)\\n   Deep work. Hard thing ALWAYS here. Strategic artifacts, frameworks.\\n3. ⚙️ ENGINE ROOM (30-45 min, afternoon if possible)\\n   Google Ads, Excel, campaign builds, keyword work.\\n4. 📋 ADMIN (20-30 min, END of day)\\n   POs, invoices, budget, compliance. Wind-down work.\\n\\nBlock body (HTML): TRAINER commentary + TASKS list with context + DRAFT MESSAGES if applicable.\\nNaming: Focus: 🧹 Sweep | Focus: 🎯 Core | Focus: ⚙️ Engine Room | Focus: 📋 Admin\\nAll: showAs=busy, reminderMinutes=15, no attendees.\\n\\n=== STEP 5: FRIDAY CALIBRATION (Fridays only) ===\\nLoad nervous-system.md. Run Loops 2-5. Session retrospective. Weekly calibration report. Append to brief. Re-email.\\n\\nAfter calibration, remind Richard to trigger the 'Portable Body Sync' hook to sync portable-body/ to GitHub. It's now a standalone hook he can run independently.\\n\\n=== EXPERIMENTATION ===\\nRead ~/shared/context/active/morning-routine-experiments.md BEFORE building the brief.\\nThis is an adaptive experiment engine, not a static queue.\\n\\n1. Check if an experiment is ACTIVE. If yes, apply its variation to this run.\\n2. After the brief is sent, log the run: date, what was different, Richard's response signals.\\n3. After 3-5 runs of an experiment, DECIDE: KEEP (adopt as baseline), REVERT, or ITERATE.\\n4. When an experiment concludes, GENERATE the next hypothesis based on:\\n   - What friction did Richard hit?\\n   - What section was skipped or asked about?\\n   - What task didn't get done despite being briefed?\\n   - What does the research suggest? (use web search for new ideas when learning plateaus)\\n5. If research surfaces a technique with overwhelming evidence (d > 0.5, multiple studies), consider applying it as a no-brainer upgrade — but still log it.\\n6. One experiment at a time. Isolate the variable. Don't stack changes.\\n\\n=== SLACK RELEVANCE FILTER ===\\nScoring model (points additive):\\n- Direct mention of Richard (prichwil, @Richard): +100 (auto high-relevance)\\n- Author is always_high_relevance in People Watch (Brandon Munday): +100\\n- Author is boosted in People Watch: +30\\n- Message contains active project keyword (from current.md): +25\\n- Message contains keyword trigger (from channel registry): +20\\n- Message is in a Tier 1 channel: +15\\n- Decision language (decided, approved, confirmed, blocked): +20\\n- Action assignment (@prichwil, Richard to, action item): +25\\n- Deadline language (by EOD, due, deadline): +15\\n- Escalation language (escalated, urgent, blocker): +20\\n- Hot topic cluster (from scan state): +15\\n- Thread > 5 replies: +10\\n\\nThreshold: 25 points. Below 25 = discard. 25-99 = relevant (include if within word cap). 100+ = high-relevance (always include).\\n\\nSignal types: decision, action-item, status-change, escalation, mention, topic-update\\nSignal fields: type, source channel, thread_ts, author, timestamp, content summary (1-2 sentences), target organ, relevance score, action flag\\n\\nDigest format: hard cap 500 words. [ACTION-RW] prefix for Richard's action items. No digest if zero signals. Plain markdown in intake/.\\n\\nIf thread has > 5 replies, retrieve full thread via batch_get_thread_replies before scoring.\\n\\n=== REPORT ===\\nCompact summary: Asana sync, drafts, aMCC, hands.md task changes, calendar blocks, experiment status.\\n\\n=== SELF-AUDIT ===\\nVerify: context completeness, brief completeness, coherence, all overdue tasks reflected in hands.md with current status."
  }
}
